1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,520
Your container just crashed. Again, at 3am, you woke up to fix it. There's a better way.

2
00:00:09,520 --> 00:00:16,400
Three eras, physical servers, resource conflicts, expensive, virtual machines, better isolation,

3
00:00:16,400 --> 00:00:22,040
but heavyweight, containers, lightweight, portable, but at scale. At scale, you need

4
00:00:22,040 --> 00:00:28,280
something to manage them. That something is Kubernetes. Open source container orchestration

5
00:00:28,280 --> 00:00:35,720
from Google released in 2014. Named from the Greek word for helmsman, abbreviated K-8S,

6
00:00:35,720 --> 00:00:43,520
8 letters between K and S. Five things that matter. Self-healing restarts crashed containers

7
00:00:43,520 --> 00:00:52,120
automatically. Scaling up or down on demand. Rollouts, zero downtime deployments. Load balancing,

8
00:00:52,440 --> 00:00:58,840
traffic distribution built in. Secrets, passwords and config managed safely. What

9
00:00:58,840 --> 00:01:05,160
Kubernetes is not. It's not a platform as a service. It doesn't build your code. It doesn't

10
00:01:05,160 --> 00:01:12,040
include databases or message buses. It's building blocks. You choose the rest. You describe the

11
00:01:12,040 --> 00:01:18,520
desired state. Three pods running. Kubernetes figures out how to get there and keeps it there.

12
00:01:18,520 --> 00:01:27,960
A container crashes. K-8s restarts it. No 3 a.m. wake up. Run the darks. Kubernetes. Episode one of 13.

